WEBVTT

00:00:00.300 --> 00:00:01.620
So I&#39;m going to talk about how
to operate.

00:00:01.620 --> 00:00:03.740
So I&#39;ve watched some of the
prior classes, and

00:00:03.740 --> 00:00:05.470
I&#39;m going to assume that
you&#39;ve already sort of

00:00:05.470 --> 00:00:07.590
hired a bunch of horrendously
resourceful people.

00:00:07.590 --> 00:00:08.570
That you&#39;ve built a product
that at

00:00:08.570 --> 00:00:09.300
least some people love.

00:00:09.300 --> 00:00:11.260
And you&#39;re probably raised
some capital.

00:00:11.260 --> 00:00:12.660
And now you&#39;re trying to build
a company.

00:00:12.660 --> 00:00:14.420
So you&#39;re, you&#39;re enforging a
product and

00:00:14.420 --> 00:00:15.800
now you have to forge a
company.

00:00:15.800 --> 00:00:16.650
And it actually argue for

00:00:16.650 --> 00:00:18.100
GM company is much more
difficult than for

00:00:18.100 --> 00:00:19.170
a GM product.

00:00:19.170 --> 00:00:20.720
Basic reason is people are
irrational.

00:00:20.720 --> 00:00:23.260
So you probably all know this
either your parents,

00:00:23.260 --> 00:00:25.170
your significant other or your
brother or sister, or

00:00:25.170 --> 00:00:27.490
your teacher, somebody in your
life is irrational.

00:00:27.490 --> 00:00:28.890
Building a company is
basically taking all

00:00:28.890 --> 00:00:30.740
the irrational people you
know, putting them in one

00:00:30.740 --> 00:00:33.830
building and then living with
them 12 hours a day at least.

00:00:33.830 --> 00:00:34.930
So, it&#39;s very challenging.

00:00:34.930 --> 00:00:36.520
Now, there&#39;s techniques for
coping with that and

00:00:36.520 --> 00:00:38.640
some people get good at it and
small people don&#39;t but

00:00:38.640 --> 00:00:40.289
that&#39;s where really what
operating is about.

00:00:41.590 --> 00:00:43.963
So basically what you&#39;re doing
when you build a company is

00:00:43.963 --> 00:00:45.179
you&#39;re building an engine.

00:00:45.179 --> 00:00:48.166
And at first you have a
drawing literally on a white

00:00:48.166 --> 00:00:50.868
board, and you&#39;re architecting
it, and it

00:00:50.868 --> 00:00:54.655
looks very conceptually clean,
and beautiful, and pretty.

00:00:54.655 --> 00:00:56.264
But when you start actually
translating to

00:00:56.264 --> 00:00:58.052
practice actually it looks
more like this, and

00:00:58.052 --> 00:00:59.760
you&#39;re holding it together
with duct tape.

00:00:59.760 --> 00:01:01.812
And it takes a lot of heroic
effort to people to

00:01:01.812 --> 00:01:03.110
actually hold it together.

00:01:03.110 --> 00:01:05.100
That&#39;s why people work 80, 100
hours a week,

00:01:05.100 --> 00:01:07.820
is that heroic effort is
actually necessary to keep

00:01:07.820 --> 00:01:08.610
this thing together.

00:01:08.610 --> 00:01:12.330
Because you don&#39;t actually yet
have polished metal in place.

00:01:12.330 --> 00:01:12.850
Eventually you

00:01:12.850 --> 00:01:14.880
want to construct a high
performance machine.

00:01:14.880 --> 00:01:17.370
A machine that actually almost
nobody really has to

00:01:17.370 --> 00:01:18.850
worry about every hour.

00:01:18.850 --> 00:01:20.330
Every minute and you know as
we

00:01:20.330 --> 00:01:23.430
used to joke about Ebay that
if Martians took over Ebay it

00:01:23.430 --> 00:01:25.470
would take like six months for
the world to notice.

00:01:25.470 --> 00:01:27.290
That&#39;s what eventually what
you want to get to.

00:01:27.290 --> 00:01:29.510
Or as Warren Buffet says, you
know, build a company that

00:01:29.510 --> 00:01:31.490
idiots could run because
eventually they will.

00:01:31.490 --> 00:01:36.010
So this is what you want
basically a performance

00:01:36.010 --> 00:01:37.069
machine that idiots can run.

00:01:38.100 --> 00:01:40.190
Now, as a leader, what is your
real job?

00:01:40.190 --> 00:01:41.268
What&#39;s your role?

00:01:41.268 --> 00:01:43.360
Strictly speaking there&#39;s only
one book that&#39;s ever written

00:01:43.360 --> 00:01:45.339
that actually explains how to
do this, it&#39;s a little old.

00:01:45.339 --> 00:01:47.196
It was written in 1992 by Andy
Grove,

00:01:47.196 --> 00:01:49.266
who&#39;s quite famous, quite
successful, and

00:01:49.266 --> 00:01:50.857
his definition of what your
job is,

00:01:50.857 --> 00:01:52.928
is to maximize the output of
an organization,

00:01:52.928 --> 00:01:55.530
your organization that you&#39;re
responsible for, CEOs,

00:01:55.530 --> 00:01:58.630
everything and a VP would be
part of the organization.

00:01:58.630 --> 00:02:00.810
And the organizations around
you, so if you&#39;re VPE,

00:02:00.810 --> 00:02:02.790
you&#39;re actually are
responsible for

00:02:02.790 --> 00:02:04.320
the performance of the product
team too, or

00:02:04.320 --> 00:02:06.760
the marketing team, because
you have influence there.

00:02:06.760 --> 00:02:10.110
So this is how measure people
and you want to focus on

00:02:10.110 --> 00:02:13.390
the output not the input the
old adage about measuring,

00:02:13.390 --> 00:02:15.780
not measuring motion and
confusing that will progress,

00:02:15.780 --> 00:02:17.950
you&#39;re measuring only
progress.

00:02:17.950 --> 00:02:19.310
And this is going to sound
like a fancy and

00:02:19.310 --> 00:02:20.300
glamorous thing to do.

00:02:21.400 --> 00:02:23.330
Maybe people get excited about
managing a whole

00:02:23.330 --> 00:02:26.390
large organization, and being
responsible for the output.

00:02:26.390 --> 00:02:28.450
But in practice, what you&#39;re
going to learn today hopefully

00:02:28.450 --> 00:02:31.240
is that it&#39;s more about things
like ordering smoothies,

00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:33.850
teaching your receptionist how
to answer the phone properly,

00:02:33.850 --> 00:02:36.060
and serving as a $10 an hour
task rabbit for

00:02:36.060 --> 00:02:37.050
your employees.

00:02:37.050 --> 00:02:38.230
So let&#39;s talk about that.

00:02:39.290 --> 00:02:40.080
So at first when you

00:02:40.080 --> 00:02:42.630
start a company everything&#39;s
going to feel like a mess.

00:02:42.630 --> 00:02:44.950
And it really should if you
have too much process,

00:02:44.950 --> 00:02:46.760
too much predictability you&#39;re
probably not

00:02:46.760 --> 00:02:49.550
innovating fast enough and
creatively enough.

00:02:49.550 --> 00:02:51.550
So it should feel like
everyday there&#39;s a new

00:02:51.550 --> 00:02:55.300
problem and what you&#39;re doing
is fundamentally triaging.

00:02:55.300 --> 00:02:57.360
So some things will look like
a problem, and

00:02:57.360 --> 00:02:59.750
they&#39;re actually a colds,
they&#39;re just going to go away.

00:02:59.750 --> 00:03:01.620
So, somebody&#39;s annoyed about
this or that.

00:03:01.620 --> 00:03:03.570
That may be a cold, and you
shouldn&#39;t stress about it,

00:03:03.570 --> 00:03:04.900
and you certainly shouldn&#39;t
allocated a lot of

00:03:04.900 --> 00:03:05.420
your time to it.

00:03:05.420 --> 00:03:08.400
And some things are going to
present themselves as colds.

00:03:08.400 --> 00:03:10.515
But just like in the emergency
room, if they&#39;re not

00:03:10.515 --> 00:03:12.693
diagnosed properly they
actually can become fatal.

00:03:12.693 --> 00:03:14.489
So what I&#39;m going to try to do
is help give you

00:03:14.489 --> 00:03:16.823
frameworks for thinking about
which things are colds and

00:03:16.823 --> 00:03:18.390
which things are potentially
fatal.

00:03:20.060 --> 00:03:21.680
So one of the most important
things I&#39;ve learned at

00:03:21.680 --> 00:03:24.240
Square is actually a concept
of editing.

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:24.960
And this is the,

00:03:24.960 --> 00:03:27.600
I think the best metaphor I&#39;ve
ever seen in like 14 years of

00:03:27.600 --> 00:03:30.470
running stuff of how to think
about your job.

00:03:30.470 --> 00:03:32.290
It&#39;s natural, it&#39;s a natural
metaphor so

00:03:32.290 --> 00:03:33.680
it&#39;s easy to take with you
every day.

00:03:33.680 --> 00:03:36.000
And actually it&#39;s easy to
transmit to each of

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:37.910
your employees so that they
can figure out

00:03:37.910 --> 00:03:39.510
wether they are editing or
writing.

00:03:39.510 --> 00:03:40.720
It&#39;s a natural construct.

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:42.360
You generally know when
someone asks you to

00:03:42.360 --> 00:03:43.220
do something.

00:03:43.220 --> 00:03:44.850
Am I more writing or am I more
editing?

00:03:44.850 --> 00:03:48.490
So an editor, as, is the best
metaphor for your job,

00:03:48.490 --> 00:03:51.150
and we&#39;re talking about the
specific things you&#39;re doing

00:03:51.150 --> 00:03:52.620
in editing.

00:03:52.620 --> 00:03:54.010
The first thing an editor
does, and

00:03:54.010 --> 00:03:55.950
you probably all had this
experience in school,

00:03:55.950 --> 00:03:58.630
is you submit a paper to a TA,
a draft to your friend.

00:03:58.630 --> 00:03:59.860
And the first thing an editor
does is

00:03:59.860 --> 00:04:02.970
they take out a red pen or
nowadays, you know online, and

00:04:02.970 --> 00:04:04.570
they start striking things.

00:04:04.570 --> 00:04:05.750
Basically eliminating things.

00:04:05.750 --> 00:04:08.090
The most important task as an
editor is to simplify,

00:04:08.090 --> 00:04:10.630
simplify, and that usually
means omitting things.

00:04:10.630 --> 00:04:14.590
So that&#39;s your job too, is to
clarify and simplify for

00:04:14.590 --> 00:04:15.810
everybody on your team,

00:04:15.810 --> 00:04:17.940
the more you simplify the
better people will perform.

00:04:17.940 --> 00:04:19.610
People cannot understand and

00:04:19.610 --> 00:04:21.910
keep track of a complicated
set of initiatives.

00:04:21.910 --> 00:04:24.230
So you&#39;ve got to distill it
down to one, two, or

00:04:24.230 --> 00:04:25.270
three things.

00:04:25.270 --> 00:04:26.610
And use a framework that they
can repeat,

00:04:26.610 --> 00:04:28.310
they can repeat without
thinking about,

00:04:28.310 --> 00:04:29.630
they can repeat to their
friends,

00:04:29.630 --> 00:04:30.480
they can repeat at night.

00:04:32.080 --> 00:04:33.580
Don&#39;t except the excuse of
complexity.

00:04:33.580 --> 00:04:35.240
A lot of people will tell you
that well this is

00:04:35.240 --> 00:04:36.590
too challenging, this is too
complicated.

00:04:36.590 --> 00:04:38.380
Well yeah, I know other people
simplify but

00:04:38.380 --> 00:04:39.150
that&#39;s not for me.

00:04:39.150 --> 00:04:40.950
This is a complicated
business.

00:04:40.950 --> 00:04:41.930
They&#39;re wrong.

00:04:41.930 --> 00:04:45.085
You can change the world, in
140 characters.

00:04:48.455 --> 00:04:50.911
You can build the most
important companies in

00:04:50.911 --> 00:04:53.910
history in a very simple to
describe concept.

00:04:53.910 --> 00:04:57.970
You can market products in
less than about 50 characters.

00:04:59.140 --> 00:05:00.100
There&#39;s no reason why you

00:05:00.100 --> 00:05:01.820
can&#39;t build your company the
same way.

00:05:01.820 --> 00:05:04.520
So force yourself to simplify
every initiative,

00:05:04.520 --> 00:05:06.630
every product, every
marketing, every,

00:05:06.630 --> 00:05:07.960
everything you do.

00:05:07.960 --> 00:05:09.790
And, and basically take out
that red,

00:05:09.790 --> 00:05:11.430
and start eliminating stuff.

00:05:12.440 --> 00:05:13.700
Second thing is, what editors
do,

00:05:13.700 --> 00:05:15.560
is they ask you clarifying
questions.

00:05:15.560 --> 00:05:16.950
So when you present a paper to
somebody,

00:05:16.950 --> 00:05:17.720
what do they usually do?

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:20.000
Do they, find some ambiguity
somewhere and

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:21.650
they say, well did you really
mean this, do you mean that,

00:05:21.650 --> 00:05:22.990
do you have an example of
this?

00:05:22.990 --> 00:05:25.190
That&#39;s what your job is, so
you&#39;re in a meeting and

00:05:25.190 --> 00:05:27.360
people are going to look to
you, and the real thing you

00:05:27.360 --> 00:05:29.780
do is you actually ask a lot
of questions.

00:05:29.780 --> 00:05:32.630
And they can be simple, basic
questions like,

00:05:32.630 --> 00:05:36.660
should we try this seven days
a week or six days?

00:05:36.660 --> 00:05:39.200
They can be fundamental
questions like,

00:05:39.200 --> 00:05:41.330
where&#39;s our competitive
advantage here?

00:05:41.330 --> 00:05:44.160
We try to this actually as
investors too

00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:46.750
some investors will ask you a
billion questions about

00:05:46.750 --> 00:05:49.560
a billion things and they&#39;ll
have you do diligence forever.

00:05:49.560 --> 00:05:52.110
We try to narrow it down to
what are one, two or

00:05:52.110 --> 00:05:53.650
three four things that
actually matter for

00:05:53.650 --> 00:05:56.070
this company and only focus on
those things.

00:05:56.070 --> 00:05:58.660
So it allows us to be more
decisive, and

00:05:58.660 --> 00:06:00.100
we can make decisions rapidly.

00:06:00.100 --> 00:06:03.090
It allows us not to distract
you from your day job,

00:06:03.090 --> 00:06:04.920
which is actually building a
company.

00:06:04.920 --> 00:06:07.035
And yet, I think we still get
to the higher fide,

00:06:07.035 --> 00:06:08.280
highest fidelity answers.

00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:09.320
We don&#39;t have all these extra,

00:06:09.320 --> 00:06:11.340
extraneous details, pieces of
data.

00:06:11.340 --> 00:06:13.850
Now it&#39;s hard, it&#39;s something
you have to practice, but

00:06:13.850 --> 00:06:16.810
when you&#39;re good at it, every
step you eliminate, Andy Grove

00:06:16.810 --> 00:06:20.560
estimated that you can improve
performance by 30-50%.

00:06:20.560 --> 00:06:22.830
The next thing you do is
allocate resources.

00:06:22.830 --> 00:06:24.110
So the editing construct,

00:06:24.110 --> 00:06:25.890
this is what editors do all
the time.

00:06:25.890 --> 00:06:28.160
They take editors from the
mid-East and

00:06:28.160 --> 00:06:30.480
covering the mid-East and they
move them to Silicon Valley,

00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:32.840
because Silicon Valley is now,
now more interesting.

00:06:32.840 --> 00:06:34.510
Or they move them to a sports
section because they want to

00:06:34.510 --> 00:06:36.680
compete on the basis of sports
with other journals and

00:06:36.680 --> 00:06:37.370
other publications.

00:06:37.370 --> 00:06:39.650
So that can be top down where
I take a bunch of,

00:06:39.650 --> 00:06:40.710
allocate resources and

00:06:40.710 --> 00:06:42.360
people would say, we&#39;re now
going over here,

00:06:42.360 --> 00:06:43.910
we&#39;re going to compete on this
basis.

00:06:43.910 --> 00:06:46.060
And then next month, next
quarter, next year,

00:06:46.060 --> 00:06:46.650
I&#39;m like well,

00:06:46.650 --> 00:06:48.780
that Middle East coverage is
getting boring and bland.

00:06:48.780 --> 00:06:49.930
We don&#39;t want to do that
anymore.

00:06:49.930 --> 00:06:52.250
Let&#39;s go chase after something
else, or it can be bottom up,

00:06:52.250 --> 00:06:53.920
just like journalists mostly
come up

00:06:53.920 --> 00:06:56.840
with their own stories, the
people who work with you.

00:06:56.840 --> 00:06:59.260
Generally should be coming up
with their own initiatives.

00:06:59.260 --> 00:07:02.231
So, a reporter will generally,
who covers Google, come up

00:07:02.231 --> 00:07:04.913
with the interesting stories
that they&#39;re hearing in

00:07:04.913 --> 00:07:07.961
aether, and propose one or two
to their editor for approval.

00:07:07.961 --> 00:07:09.994
But it&#39;s not like the editor
is saying, go cover Google,

00:07:09.994 --> 00:07:10.998
and this is the angle I want.

00:07:10.998 --> 00:07:12.227
Once in a while they do that,
but

00:07:12.227 --> 00:07:13.915
that&#39;s not the date, the day,
the meat and

00:07:13.915 --> 00:07:16.520
potatoes of what a journalist
does every day.

00:07:16.520 --> 00:07:19.500
Your goal over time is to
actually use less red

00:07:19.500 --> 00:07:20.650
ink every day.

00:07:20.650 --> 00:07:22.474
So one way of measuring how
well you&#39;re doing in

00:07:22.474 --> 00:07:23.158
communicating to

00:07:23.158 --> 00:07:25.446
your colleagues about what&#39;s
important and what&#39;s not.

00:07:25.446 --> 00:07:27.119
What, why some things are
important,

00:07:27.119 --> 00:07:28.031
some things are not,

00:07:28.031 --> 00:07:30.470
is how much red ink you&#39;re
pulling out every day.

00:07:30.470 --> 00:07:31.930
It&#39;s okay if you have a bad
day and

00:07:31.930 --> 00:07:33.490
the red inks all over the
place.

00:07:33.490 --> 00:07:34.970
But it&#39;s not okay if the red
ink next month is

00:07:34.970 --> 00:07:36.350
more is more than it was last
month,

00:07:36.350 --> 00:07:37.820
if the next quarter is more
than this.

00:07:37.820 --> 00:07:41.380
So measure yourself of how
much red ink you&#39;re creating.

00:07:41.380 --> 00:07:44.450
The other thing that&#39;s very
important that actually isn&#39;t

00:07:44.450 --> 00:07:46.380
as intuitive to a lot of
people is,

00:07:46.380 --> 00:07:49.140
the job of an editor is to
ensure consistent voice.

00:07:49.140 --> 00:07:50.880
So if any of you read The
Economist,

00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:53.460
you can tell that there&#39;s one
consistent voice.

00:07:53.460 --> 00:07:56.250
You can pick up any article,
any post in The Economist, and

00:07:56.250 --> 00:07:58.360
if feels like it&#39;s written by
the same person.

00:07:58.360 --> 00:07:59.980
Ideally your company should
feel like,

00:07:59.980 --> 00:08:01.480
on your website and your PR
release,

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:03.700
on your packaging, if it&#39;s a
physical product.

00:08:03.700 --> 00:08:05.810
Anywhere on your recruiting
pages to feel like it

00:08:05.810 --> 00:08:07.110
was written by one person.

00:08:07.110 --> 00:08:08.570
That&#39;s extremely difficult to
do,

00:08:08.570 --> 00:08:10.300
and first you&#39;re going to be
tempted to do

00:08:10.300 --> 00:08:13.390
that yourself which is okay
for a founder to that.

00:08:13.390 --> 00:08:15.060
Him or herself initially.

00:08:15.060 --> 00:08:17.230
Over time you do not want to
be doing all of

00:08:17.230 --> 00:08:19.920
the consistent voice editing
by yourself.

00:08:19.920 --> 00:08:21.190
You are a trained people so

00:08:21.190 --> 00:08:22.950
that they can recognize the
differences in voice.

00:08:22.950 --> 00:08:24.430
So if you see this website
page it

00:08:24.430 --> 00:08:26.190
looks very different than the
recruiting page.

00:08:26.190 --> 00:08:28.410
You start by asking questions
why is that?

00:08:28.410 --> 00:08:29.550
Is the reporting messed up?

00:08:29.550 --> 00:08:30.910
Is the leaders over here not

00:08:30.910 --> 00:08:32.960
really understanding the voice
of the company?

00:08:32.960 --> 00:08:35.110
So, you&#39;ve gotta, you have to
fix that over time.

00:08:35.110 --> 00:08:36.920
But you want to start with the
objective of

00:08:36.920 --> 00:08:39.280
everything should feel exactly
the same.

00:08:39.280 --> 00:08:41.250
It&#39;s quite, quite difficult in
practice.

00:08:41.250 --> 00:08:43.800
Almost every company has at
least one piece

00:08:43.800 --> 00:08:46.470
of the organization that isn&#39;t
exactly on the same voice.

00:08:46.470 --> 00:08:47.980
At Apple, which is notorious,
you know,

00:08:47.980 --> 00:08:50.130
even under Steve&#39;s regime,
which was notorious for

00:08:50.130 --> 00:08:51.610
getting this right.

00:08:51.610 --> 00:08:53.710
If you asked someone who
worked at Apple, talk,

00:08:53.710 --> 00:08:56.030
asked them about the internal
tools about recruiting.

